## Highlights

- ðŸ”¥ **Hot Reload** â€” automatic router loading and file watching for instant development cycles
- ðŸŽ­ **Role System** â€” pre-configured roles (owner, support, tester, etc) and selector UI
- ðŸ“š **Pagination** â€” easy pagination over text and media using inline buttons
- ðŸ’¬ **FSM Toolkit** â€” interactive confirmations, questionnaires, and mockable message flow
- ðŸš€ **CLI Generator** â€” `$ raito init` creates a ready-to-use bot template in seconds
- âŒ¨ï¸ **Keyboard Factory** â€” static and dynamic generation
- ðŸ› ï¸ **Command Registration** â€” automatic setup of bot commands with descriptions for each
- ðŸ–¼ï¸ **Album Support** â€” groups media albums and passes them to handlers
- ðŸ›¡ï¸ **Rate Limiting** â€” apply global or per-command throttling via decorators or middleware
- ðŸ’¾ **Database Storages** â€” optional JSON & SQL support
- ðŸ§ª **REPL** â€” execute async Python in context (`_msg`, `_user`, `_raito`)
- ðŸ” **Params Parser** â€” extracts and validates command arguments
- âœï¸ **Logging Formatter** â€” beautiful, readable logs out of the box
- ðŸ“Š **Metrics** â€” inspect memory usage, uptime, and caching stats


## Installation

```bash
pip install -U raito
```


## Quick Start

```python
import asyncio

from aiogram import Bot, Dispatcher
from raito import Raito


async def main() -> None:
    bot = Bot(token="TOKEN")
    dispatcher = Dispatcher()
    raito = Raito(dispatcher, "src/handlers")

    await raito.setup()
    await dispatcher.start_polling(bot)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    asyncio.run(main())
```

## Why Raito?

Raito speeds up your bot development by removing the boring parts â€” no more boilerplate, no more manual restarts, no more duplicated code across projects. \
Everything that used to slow you down is already solved.


## Showcases

#### ðŸ“¦ Handling Commands

You can control access to commands using `@rt.roles`

The `@rt.description` decorator adds a description to each command â€” they will show up in the slash menu automatically.

For commands like `/ban 1234`, use `@rt.params` to extract and validate the arguments.

Limit command usage with `@rt.limiter` and control the rate by mode.

```python
@router.message(filters.Command("ban"), OWNER | ADMINISTRATOR | MODERATOR)
@rt.description("Ban a user")
@rt.limiter(300, mode="chat")
@rt.params(user_id=int)
async def ban(message: types.Message, user_id: int, bot: Bot):
    await bot.ban_chat_member(chat_id=message.chat.id, user_id=user_id)
    await message.answer(text="âœ… User banned successfully!")
```

---

#### ðŸ”¥ Hot-Reload & Router Management

Whenever you change a file with handlers, Raito automatically reloads it without restarting the bot.

You can also manage your routers manually using the `.rt load`, `.rt unload`, `.rt reload`, or `.rt routers` commands in the bot.

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c7ecfb7e-b709-4f92-9de3-efc4982cc926

---

